Congress Will Propel Sweeping Conservative Agenda. The Most Ambitious Agenda Since The 1920s Washington Post: For six years, since they took back the House of Representatives, Republicans have added to a pile of legislation that moldered outside the White House. When the 115th Congress begins this week, with Republicans firmly in charge of the House and Senate, much of that legislation will form the basis of the most ambitious conservative policy agenda since the 1920s. A soon-to-be-inaugurated Donald Trump seems ready to sign much of it into law. House Speaker Paul Ryan (R-WI) says negotiations with the incoming Trump administration are mostly “on timeline, on an execution strategy.” Congressional Republicans are poised to have more influence over the national agenda in 2017 than congressional Democrats did after the 2008 election that put Obama in the White House with his party in control on Capitol Hill. While the Democratic majority in 2009 was larger than the GOP advantage this year, the Democrats were hamstrung in ways they came to regret. Republicans have made no attempt to frame their agenda as bipartisan. Senate Republicans favor using a procedure known as “budget reconciliation,” in which measures can be passed with a simple 51-vote majority rather than a filibuster-proof 60 votes, to tackle Obamacare and to undo much of the 2010 Dodd-Frank financial reform. In addition, some GOP leaders have begun planning strategies for how to effectively kill the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. “I’d like to repeal the whole thing, period,” Senate Banking Committee Chairman Richard Shelby said of Dodd-Frank. The reconciliation process is also likely to be used to pass tax changes, which both Trump and congressional Republicans want to use to lower rates and end the estate tax. Republicans also are examining ways to undo many of the regulations and other orders enacted by Obama and his administration, including ones issued in the weeks since Trump’s victory. GOP leaders have cited the 21-year old Congressional Review Act, which allows Congress to cast simple majority votes of disapproval for regulations, as a way to block anything the administration has ordered since June 2016. Since its passage, the CRA has been used only once. But now 200 regulations are vulnerable to a disapproval vote. They include “burdensome” school lunch standards, tobacco regulations, laws that set higher wages for contractors and elements of the Paris climate-change agreement. Republicans intend to supplement the CRA by enacting a law that would subject any regulation with an economic impact greater than $100 million to a vote of Congress, a change that would have prevented nearly every climate or employment rule change of the Obama years. The measure, called the Regulations From the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act, or Reins, is a conservative priority that passed the Republican House in 2011, 2013 and 2015 with backing from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. Republican aides now hope for a vote on Reins in the coming days so it can be sent for Trump’s signature immediately after he is sworn in on Jan. 20. Some Republican lawmakers also want legislation that would stop courts from deferring to federal agencies’ interpretations of statutes — a practice known as “Chevron deference,” after the 1984 Supreme Court case that went against the energy company — and have them instead defer to Congress. Legislation to allow concealed weapons to be carried across state lines, a major goal of the National Rifle Association, was endorsed by Trump and may be hard for red-state Democrats to oppose. You can read the full article at: https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/claiming-mandate-gop-congress-lays-plans-to-propel-sweeping-conservative-agenda/2017/01/01/9840338a-ceee-11e6-b8a2-8c2a61b0436f_story.html?hpid=hp_rhp-top-table-main_congress-820pm%3Ahomepage%2Fstory

People who have no need of these spaces and insist on complaining about them don't even understand what they are for. They think people just want to be coddles and "not get their feelings hurt." In reality, these spaces are often used by people who have experienced some sort of trauma and/or need a short reprieve from the daily stresses of living in a racist, sexist, homophobic society. When you make fun of these spaces, you're basically telling these people "You don't deserve to not have a place where people understand how to handle someone who has been sexually abused," or "You don't deserve a place where you can be guaranteed to not be demeaned or threatened because of the color of your skin for a little while," or "You don't deserve a place where you know no one will try to harm you because of who you love." Safe spaces have been around for a long time, even if they weren't called such. Gay bars, women's clinics, and domestic violence shelters were all at one point considered to be safe spaces. Unfortunately, given that these places have become prone to attack by the very people they are trying to keep themselves safe from, alternatives had to be set up. In short, don't be an asshole. Everyone deserves to feel safe.

When the 115th Congress begins this week, with Republicans firmly in charge of the House and Senate, much of that legislation will form the basis of the most ambitious conservative policy agenda since the 1920s. A soon-to-be-inaugurated Donald Trump seems ready to sign much of it into law. House Speaker Paul Ryan (R-WI) says negotiations with the incoming Trump administration are mostly “on timeline, on an execution strategy.” Congressional Republicans are poised to have more influence over the national agenda in 2017 than congressional Democrats did after the 2008 election that put Obama in the White House with his party in control on Capitol Hill. While the Democratic majority in 2009 was larger than the GOP advantage this year, the Democrats were hamstrung in ways they came to regret. Republicans have made no attempt to frame their agenda as bipartisan. Senate Republicans favor using a procedure known as “budget reconciliation,” in which measures can be passed with a simple 51-vote majority rather than a filibuster-proof 60 votes, to tackle Obamacare and to undo much of the 2010 Dodd-Frank financial reform. In addition, some GOP leaders have begun planning strategies for how to effectively kill the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. “I’d like to repeal the whole thing, period,” Senate Banking Committee Chairman Richard Shelby said of Dodd-Frank. The reconciliation process is also likely to be used to pass tax changes, which both Trump and congressional Republicans want to use to lower rates and end the estate tax. Republicans also are examining ways to undo many of the regulations and other orders enacted by Obama and his administration, including ones issued in the weeks since Trump’s victory. GOP leaders have cited the 21-year old Congressional Review Act, which allows Congress to cast simple majority votes of disapproval for regulations, as a way to block anything the administration has ordered since June 2016. Since its passage, the CRA has been used only once. But now 200 regulations are vulnerable to a disapproval vote. They include “burdensome” school lunch standards, tobacco regulations, laws that set higher wages for contractors and elements of the Paris climate-change agreement. Republicans intend to supplement the CRA by enacting a law that would subject any regulation with an economic impact greater than $100 million to a vote of Congress, a change that would have prevented nearly every climate or employment rule change of the Obama years. The measure, called the Regulations From the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act, or Reins, is a conservative priority that passed the Republican House in 2011, 2013 and 2015 with backing from the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. Republican aides now hope for a vote on Reins in the coming days so it can be sent for Trump’s signature immediately after he is sworn in on Jan. 20. Some Republican lawmakers also want legislation that would stop courts from deferring to federal agencies’ interpretations of statutes — a practice known as “Chevron deference,” after the 1984 Supreme Court case that went against the energy company — and have them instead defer to Congress. Legislation to allow concealed weapons to be carried across state lines, a major goal of the National Rifle Association, was endorsed by Trump and may be hard for red-state Democrats to oppose. People who have no need of these spaces and insist on complaining about them don't even understand what they are for. They think people just want to be coddles and "not get their feelings hurt." In reality, these spaces are often used by people who have experienced some sort of trauma and/or need a short reprieve from the daily stresses of living in a racist, sexist, homophobic society. When you make fun of these spaces, you're basically telling these people "You don't deserve to not have a place where people understand how to handle someone who has been sexually abused," or "You don't deserve a place where you can be guaranteed to not be demeaned or threatened because of the color of your skin for a little while," or "You don't deserve a place where you know no one will try to harm you because of who you love." Safe spaces have been around for a long time, even if they weren't called such. Gay bars, women's clinics, and domestic violence shelters were all at one point considered to be safe spaces. Unfortunately, given that these places have become prone to attack by the very people they are trying to keep themselves safe from, alternatives had to be set up. In short, don't be an asshole. Everyone deserves to feel safe.
